Subtle shifts raise hopes for a cease-fire in Ukraine.
Image
President Vladimir V. Putin meeting with members of the Security Council via a video link last week. The Kremlin has signaled it is no longer demanding regime change in Ukraine. Credit... Andrey Gorshkov/Sputnik, via Reuters

ISTANBUL â€” When President Vladimir V. Putin launched his invasion two weeks ago, he said a primary goal was the â€œdenazificationâ€ of Ukraine. He referred to the Ukrainian government as a â€œgang of drug addicts and neo-Nazis,â€ making it clear that his aim was to topple it.

But in recent days, the language has shifted, with the Kremlin signaling that Mr. Putin is no longer bent on regime change in Kyiv. It is a subtle shift, and it may be a head-fake; but it is prompting officials who have scrambled to mediate to believe that Mr. Putin may be seeking a negotiated way out of a war that has become a much bloodier slog than he expected.

On Thursday, Foreign Minister Sergey V. Lavrov of Russia is expected to meet his Ukrainian counterpart, Dmytro Kuleba, in Turkey, in the highest-level talks between the two countries since the war began on Feb. 24. President Recep Tayyip Erdogan of Turkey, whose top diplomat has held a total of 10 calls with Mr. Lavrov and Mr. Kuleba since the start of the war, said on Wednesday that the meeting could â€œcrack the door open to a permanent cease-fire.â€

Leading up to the meeting, both sides have softened their public positions, though they remain far apart. Russia has narrowed its demands to focus on Ukrainian â€œneutralityâ€ and the status of its Russian-occupied regions, and declared on Wednesday that Russia was not seeking to â€œoverthrowâ€ Ukraineâ€™s government. President Volodymyr Zelensky of Ukraine on Tuesday suggested he was open to revising Ukraineâ€™s constitutionally enshrined aspiration to join NATO, and even to a compromise over the status of Ukrainian territory now controlled by Russia.

â€œThe changes are noticeable,â€ Ivan Timofeev, the director of programs at the government-funded Russian International Affairs Council, said of the evolution in Russiaâ€™s negotiating position. â€œThis position has become more realistic.â€

The Kremlinâ€™s position now, according to comments this week by its spokesman, Dmitri S. Peskov, is that Ukraine must recognize Russian sovereignty over Crimea and the independence of the Russian-backed, separatist â€œpeopleâ€™s republicsâ€ in the countryâ€™s east and enshrine a status of neutrality in its constitution. That is still far from what Mr. Zelensky has said he would be willing to accept â€” and it could also puncture Mr. Putinâ€™s strongman image at home, opening him up to criticism that he waged an enormous war for limited gain.
Image
Diplomats walking out in protest as Russiaâ€™s foreign minister, Sergey V. Lavrov,  addressed the Conference on Disarmament in Geneva last week. Mr. Lavrov is meeting his Ukrainian counterpart in Turkey on Thursday. Credit... Pool photo by Salvatore Di Nolfi

â€œRegarding NATO, I have cooled down regarding this question a long time ago, after we understood that NATO is not prepared to accept Ukraine,â€ Mr. Zelensky said in an interview with ABC News on Tuesday.

Ukraine was also willing to discuss how the breakaway territories â€œwill live on,â€ Mr. Zelensky added. â€œWhat is important to me is how the people in those territories are going to live who want to be part of Ukraine. The question is more difficult than simply acknowledging them.â€

With Russia escalating its bombardment of Ukrainian cities in recent days, there are few signs on the ground that the Kremlin is ready to back down. For Mr. Putin, analysts say, the fate of Ukraine is fundamental to how he sees his legacy: that of a leader who reunited what he claims are historically Russian lands that were divided by the collapse of the Soviet Union. In the early days of the conflict, he repeatedly called on the Ukrainian army to lay down its arms and negotiate, apparently expecting Ukrainians to rally to Russiaâ€™s side.

But Ukraineâ€™s fierce resistance, and the Westâ€™s unity in imposing crushing sanctions, has revealed that Mr. Putin greatly miscalculated. Now, Mr. Timofeev says, the Kremlin must choose â€œbetween the lesser of two evilsâ€: either accept a compromise that could keep a pro-Western government in Kyiv, or fight on, risking enormous casualties both in the Russian army and among Ukrainians.

â€œHe has a clear plan right now to brutalize Ukraine. But to what end?â€ U.S. Secretary of State Antony J. Blinken said on Wednesday. â€œWhat is his endgame?â€

The best option, Mr. Blinken said, was to maintain extreme pressure on Russia and hope that Mr. Putin â€œwill decide to try to finally cut the losses that heâ€™s inflicted on himself and inflicted on the Russian people.â€
Image
A cruise missile struck barracks of the Ukrainian armyâ€™s elite 79th Brigade in Mykolaiv, Ukraine. As the war has bogged down, Russian forces have stepped up their bombardment of Ukrainian targets, including cities. Credit... Tyler Hicks/The New York Times

The United States has avoided engaging at a high level with the Kremlin since the war began, after an intense diplomatic push by Mr. Blinken and President Biden in the months before the invasion. Instead, amid the fighting, some American allies have stepped up their own efforts to halt the war â€” in particular, Israel and Turkey, which both have close ties to Russia as well as to Ukraine.

Prime Minister Naftali Bennett flew to Moscow last Saturday on an urgent mission to see Mr. Putin, making the trip even though it was the Jewish Sabbath. He spoke to Mr. Putin by phone Tuesday, their fifth conversation since the war began.

Israeli officials believe that Mr. Bennett is in a unique position to communicate messages between the two sides because Israel is one of the few countries with a relatively functional relationship with both Kyiv and Moscow. Israel coordinates with Russia over its military activity in Syria and wants to protect the Jewish minorities in both Russia and Ukraine.

In a separate effort, Turkey is also trying to facilitate talks between the two sides. Mevlut Cavusoglu, the Turkish foreign minister, has spoken to Mr. Lavrov, his Russian counterpart, four times and to Mr. Kuleba, his Ukrainian counterpart, six times since the outbreak of war.

Turkey is a NATO ally, has provided Ukraine with lethally effective armed drones and has strong cultural ties to the Crimean Tatar minority in Russian-occupied Crimea. But Mr. Erdogan has also formed a strong personal bond to Mr. Putin and, unlike other NATO leaders, has stopped short of imposing sanctions against Russia over the invasion.

â€œTurkeyâ€™s key position that it is able to talk to both parties is appreciated in the whole world,â€ Mr. Erdogan said on Wednesday, ahead of the talks between Mr. Lavrov and Mr. Kuleba. â€œI hope this meeting will crack the door open to a permanent cease-fire.â€
Image
Secretary of State Antony Blinken and Dmytro Kuleba, Ukraineâ€™s foreign minister, speaking at the Ukraine-Poland border in Korczowa, Poland, on Saturday. Credit... Pool photo by Olivier Douliery

A cease-fire would bring relief to the Ukrainian public but it would not necessarily mean the end of the war. Instead, analysts cautioned, both sides could use it to build up strength ahead of a further escalation in the fighting.

â€œFor Ukraine, they would use it to get some civilians into safety but also continue receiving resupply from the West,â€ said Ozgur Unluhisarcikli , director in Ankara, Turkey, of the German Marshall Fund of the United States. â€œI am afraid both sides would use such a cease-fire to boost their offensives.â€

Russian and Ukrainian officials have already held three rounds of talks in Belarus since the start of the war, clashing over issues such as limited cease-fires and civilian evacuations that could help clear the way for a broader settlement. Mr. Peskov described Thursdayâ€™s meeting of foreign ministers, which will take place in the Turkish resort of Antalya, as â€œa very important continuation of the negotiation process.â€

â€œThe Russian position has been formulated and relayed to the Ukrainian negotiators,â€ Mr. Peskov said. â€œWe are interested in having new rounds of contacts as quickly as possible.â€

On Monday, the White House press secretary, Jen Psaki, said that the Biden administration supports the diplomacy with Mr. Putin by other foreign leaders, including Mr. Bennett, so long as those leaders also engage with Ukraineâ€™s government. She added that the United States also speaks to Mr. Putinâ€™s interlocutors â€œbefore and after all of these conversations.â€

Mr. Biden spoke jointly about Ukraine on Friday with President Emmanuel Macron of France and Chancellor Olaf Scholz of Germany, along with Prime Minister Boris Johnson of Britain. The White House said that Mr. Macron and Mr. Scholz discussed their recent conversations with the Russian leader.
Image
Ukrainian soldiers stand guard in Maidan Square in central Kyiv. Recent shifts in the diplomatic winds have raised hopes that a bloody Russian invasion of the Ukrainian capital could be avoided.  Credit... Lynsey Addario for The New York Times

As for a direct call between Mr. Biden and Mr. Putin, Ms. Psaki said that â€œnow is not the moment,â€ given the Russian leaderâ€™s â€œbrutal, horrificâ€ invasion.

â€œBut that doesnâ€™t mean he will never,â€ she added. â€œWe assess that as time goes on.â€

Samuel Charap, a former U.S. State Department official and a Russia analyst with the Rand Corporation, said the United States has not prioritized diplomacy over economic and military pressure against Mr. Putin.

â€œI assume thatâ€™s because up to this point they think itâ€™s a dead end, and thereâ€™s no convincing the Russians to change their immediate war aims,â€ Mr. Charap said, warning that the approach could limit the possibilities for a diplomatic endgame. â€œIn Putinâ€™s view, the president of the United States is the only interlocutor who matters.â€

He added that direct channels of communication have inherent value even if an agreement looks unlikely, because they can set the stage for later negotiations, avoid misinterpretations and potentially help assuage Mr. Putinâ€™s most paranoid beliefs, including that the West is trying to engineer his overthrow.

â€œPutinâ€™s policies and views might be changing, and the only way you can find that out is by talking to him,â€ Mr. Charap said.

