Ms. Perebyinisâ€™ employer, SE Ranking, a software company with offices in California and London, had encouraged employees to leave Ukraine immediately once the fighting started. It had even rented rooms for them in Poland, Mr. Perebyinis said. But his wife delayed her departure because of uncertainty over how to evacuate her mother, who has Alzheimerâ€™s disease.

A colleague at work, Anastasia Avetysian, said that SE Ranking had provided emergency funds for employees to evacuate and that Ms. Perebyinis, as the chief accountant in Ukraine, had been busy in her final days disbursing them.

â€œWe were all in touch with her,â€ Ms. Avetysian said in a telephone interview. â€œEven when she was hiding in the basement, she was optimistic and joking in our group chat that the company would now need to do a special operation to get them out, like â€˜Saving Private Ryan.â€™â€

But behind the jokes was a period of waiting and intense worrying, Mr. Perebyinis said. His son, Mykyta, started sleeping during the day and staying up all night, keeping a vigil over his mother and sister. When there were sounds of fighting, he woke them up and all three would move into a corridor, away from the windows. â€œMy son was under a lot of stress,â€ Mr. Perebyinis said.
Image
The familyâ€™s apartment building, damaged by Russian shelling earlier this month. Credit... Serhiy Perebyinis
Image
